<topic template="Default" lasteditedby="cimpo" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:noNamespaceSchemaLocation="../helpproject.xsd">
  <title translate="true">How Regex is Used</title>
  <body>
    <header>
      <para styleclass="Heading1"><text styleclass="Heading1" translate="true">How Regex is Used</text></para>
    </header>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">Visual Studio 2005-2010 uses a different regex syntax than VS 2012 and higher. VS 2012 and higher uses exactly the same syntax as .NET framework regex.</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-weight:bold;" translate="true">Newlines</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">Visual Studio 2005-2010 uses </text><text styleclass="Code Example" style="font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold;" translate="true">\n</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> for any combination of CR and LF characters. In VS 2012 and higher, the newlines are represented by more complicated search pattern </text><text styleclass="Code Example" style="font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold;" translate="true">((\r\n)|\n|\r)</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">.</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-weight:bold;" translate="true">Replacing with an empty text</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">Unfortunatelly, it&apos;s not possible to pre-populate the </text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-weight:bold;" translate="true">Replace with</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> field directly with an empty text (if you want to delete a text) because VS automatically inserts the last non-empty value from the history. To prevent this, we must pass some non-empty value which produces an empty text.</text></para>
    <list id="71" type="ul" listtype="bullet" formatstring="&#183;" format-charset="SYMBOL_CHARSET" levelreset="true" legalstyle="false" startfrom="1" styleclass="Normal" style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; color:#000000;">
      <li styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">In VS 2005-2010, </text><text styleclass="Code Example" style="font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold;" translate="true">\number</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> is used for group replacement. The ninth regex tagged expression seems good for this as it is very unlikely that user will add 9 tagged expressions in Find field in built-in VS Find dialog after it is pre-filled with the extension. So </text><text styleclass="Code Example" style="font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold;" translate="true">\9</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> is used in Replace with field.</text></li>
      <li styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">Starting with VS 2012, the regex syntax in Find dialog has changed. It is now the same as .NET regex where $ is used for group replacement. So we substitute the last group (which needs to be defined in &apos;Find what&apos; and it must be empty). The last group substitute is </text><text styleclass="Code Example" style="font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold;" translate="true">$+</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">. As already mentioned, if </text><text styleclass="Code Example" style="font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold;" translate="true">$+</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> is used in </text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-weight:bold;" translate="true">Replace with</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> field, then we must append the last (and only) (and empty) group in Find what field: </text><text styleclass="Code Example" style="font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold;" translate="true">()</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">.</text></li>
    </list>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-weight:bold;" translate="true">Escaping special characters</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">Many characters have special meaning in regex syntax. therefore they need to be escaped. They differ by VS version and whether they are in </text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-weight:bold;" translate="true">Find what</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> or </text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-weight:bold;" translate="true">Replace with</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> field. These characters are:</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example" style="margin-left:24px;"><text styleclass="Code Example" style="font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold;" translate="true">\.*+^$&gt;&lt;[]|{}:@#()~?!</text></para>
  </body>
</topic>
